for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    prosper_clean[var] = prosper_clean[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Prosper dataset consists of 82 attributes with 113066 unique listings. I've decided to focus on ~23 important features which include loan member characteristics and what might be driving factors of probability of loan payment. These variables differ from numeric to categorical. You can explore all variable definitions here.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of this dataset will be user, or who will be referred to in this analysis as "borrower", defined characteristics such as, state of residence, monthly income, credit rating, employment status, delinquent payments, borrower rate, occupation, loan status, among others to learn more about the Prosper borrower. This will help with determining not only the profile and risk of the borrower but, also potentially their ability and willingness to pay off the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the monthly income, debt to income ratio, monthly loan payments, employment status, occupation, credit grade ranges, and borrower state along with borrower rate and APR will be a great determiner in learning if our users will be able to payoff their loans.

Univariate Exploration¶

Let's look at Borrower Occupation to see any patterns or determine if there is more interest for loans in particular fields. This can help with Prosper Loan marketing teams and their efforts in marketing strategies.¶

We see the top occupation is Other which doesn't supply much information however, the Professional is next, which can mean many things like management positions, or even a professional althlete, while Computer Programmer is third with Executive, and Teacher behind. Overall, we have education, technology, professionals and other, with some ambiguity, in the top 5.¶

Let's now look at our Borrower Rate, which refers to an interest rate additional cost of borrowing the principal loan amount¶

Below we can see this is not exactly a normal distribution but, can be interpreted more as random skewness with different peaks with slight right skewness with peak at 0.15, a mean of 0.19, and then a peak again after 0.20 but, a drop around the 4000 frequency range with a random spike at ~0.32¶

Below we can see a similar pattern of random skewnness and a peak at ~0.18 and ~0.21, while our mean of ~0.22 then seems to drop to about a 2700 frequency range but, thene rise slightly again just before 0.30 with a random peak again at ~0.36.¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The heatmap by correlation coefficient was helpful to see that really the only true features that had strong relationships were Borrower APR, Borrower Rate, Estimated Loss and Estimated Return. When reading more about interest rate, and APR you can see how that would impact a decision to take out a loan or wait until potentially a better rate was available.

The other feature was borrower monthly income which ranged from 0 to over 100,000 and yet, most in the range of 25,000 to 100,000 had either less than 5000 principal outstanding or less than 100,000 delinquent but, fewer overall had delinquency. The outliers were two data points one delinquent over 400,000 in the 25,000 to 49,999 income range, and one delinquent about 300,000 and had about 10,000 principal outstanding.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The interesting or surprising interactions between features were learning that there were Borrowers marked as not employed for income range and yet one Borrower owned about $100,000.

Overall, most Borrowers had income ranges from 25,000 to 49,999 which could be considered in the 12% and a portion of the 22% single population U.S. tax bracket or 12% if married (filing jointly) for 2019.
